			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2015</a> paper:</span><br><i>Example-based validation of domain-specific visual languages</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/JesúsJLópezFernández.html">Jesús J. López-Fernández</a>, <a href="../profile/EstherGuerra.html">Esther Guerra</a>, <a href="../profile/JuandeLara.html">Juan de Lara</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/2814251.2814256">10.1145/2814251.2814256</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5c.html"><span class="tagM">T5C: Testing</span></a><ul><li> The main focus is validating DSL definitions by checking them against example instances (testing/validation).
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> It targets domain-specific languages, specifically domain-specific *visual* languages.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4f.html"><span class="tagL">T4F: Visualisation</span></a><ul><li> Because the DSLs are visual, the work directly involves graphical notation and its interpretation.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> The approach is motivated by and discussed in the context of tool support for DSL engineering.
</li></ul></li></ul>
